Problem 1

gcd_fuction Pseudocode

Program start 
Input numeric values a, b
If a or b is less than 1
    Throw error 
If a or b is not an integer
    Throw error 
Set bigger to larger of a and b
Set smaller to smaller of a and b
Set r to 1
While r does not equal 0
    Set r to remainder of bigger divided by smaller
    Set bigger to smaller 
    If r is not 0
        Set smaller to r
Return smaller

gcd_function calls

## [1] 21

## [1] 38

gcd_3 Pseudocode

Program start 
Input numeric values a, b, c
Set g to the output of calling gcd() on a and b
Set final to the output of calling gcd() on g and c
Return final

Problem 2

is_prime Pseudocode

Program start 
Input a vector x of numeric values
Set final to vector of equal length to x containing logical values 
For i in range 1 through the length of x
    Set test to TRUE
    If x[i] = 2
        Set test to TRUE
    If x[i] < 2 or is not an integer
        Set test to FALSE
    Else 
        For j in range 2 through x[i] – 1
            If the remainder of x[i] divided by j is equal to 0
                Set test to FALSE
    Set final[i] to test
Return final

is_prime function calls

is_prime(9)
## [1] FALSE
is_prime(c(2,97,23,51,119, -1, 0,1.5))
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

get_factors pseudocode

Program start
Input a positive integer value for parameter y
Create an empty vector called final
If y is not a positive integer value 
    Throw a stop error 
If y is equal to 1
    Set final to y
If y is not prime
    While y is not prime
        Create an empty vector called l
        Find all of the factors of y and append them to l
        Find the smallest factor of l (this will be a prime number)
        Add this number to the final vector
        Find the quotient of y divided by the smallest factor of y
        Set this new value to y 
    When y is prime and the above loop ends, add this value to the final vector 
If y is prime (and passes the above cases)
    Set final to y
Return final
